<example id="fs-id1753039"><exercise id="fs-id1723344"><problem id="fs-id1870989">
<para id="fs-id1171488049644">One number is ten more than twice another. Their sum is one. Find the numbers.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1534142">
<title>Solution</title>

<table id="eip-id1168468367283" class="unnumbered unstyled" summary="Step 1 says to read the problem. “Read” is in bold. Step 2 says to identify what you are looking for. “Identify” is in bold. Beside this is written, “two numbers.” Step 3 says, “Name. Choose a variable.” The word “name” is written in bold. Beside this, it says “let x equal the first number.” Then it says, “one number is ten more than twice another,” and shows 2x plus 10 equals second number. Step 4 says, “Translate. Restate as one sentence. Translate into an equation.” The first “translate” is written in bold. Beside this is written, “Their sum is one. The sum of the two numbers is 1. x plus 2x plus 10 equals 1.” Step 5 says, “Solve the equation.” The word “solve” is in bold. Next to this step is x plus parentheses 2x plus 10 equals 1. Below this are instructions to combine like terms and the equation 3x plus 10 equals 1. Below this, subtract 10 from each side, and 3x equals negative 9. Below this, divide each side by 3 to get the first number. x equals negative 3. Then substitute to get the second number. 2x plus 10 equals 2 times a red negative 3 plus 10 equals 4. Step 6 says, “Check. Is 4 equal to 10 more than twice negative 3?” The word “check” is in bold. Beside this is 2 times negative 3 plus 10 equals 4. Below this, negative 6 plus 10 equals 4. Then, 4 equals 4, followed by a check mark. Then, “Is their sum 1?” Beside this is negative 3 plus 4 equals 1. Below this, 1 equals 1, followed by a check mark. Step 7 says to answer the question. “Answer” is in bold. The answer says, “The numbers are negative 3 and 4.”"><label/>
<tgroup cols="2"><tbody>
<row>
<entry>Step 1. <emphasis effect="bold">Read</emphasis> the problem.</entry>
<entry/>
<entry/>
</row>
 <row>
 <entry>Step 2. <emphasis effect="bold">Identify</emphasis> what you are looking for.</entry>
<entry/>
  <entry>two numbers</entry>
 </row>
 <row>
 <entry>Step 3. <emphasis effect="bold">Name.</emphasis> Choose a variable.<newline/>One number is ten more than twice another.</entry>
<entry/>
 <entry>Let <emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> = 1<sup>st</sup> number<newline/>2<emphasis effect="italics">x</emphasis> + 10 = 2<sup>nd</sup> number</entry>
 </row>
 <row>
 <entry>Step 4. <emphasis effect="bold">Translate.</emphasis> Restate as one sentence.</entry>
<entry/>
<entry>Their sum is one.</entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Translate into an equation</entry>
<entry/>
 <entry><media id="eip-id1168468246897" alt="."><image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_09_01_027_img-01.png"/></media></entry>
 </row>
 <row>
 <entry>Step 5. <emphasis effect="bold">Solve</emphasis> the equation.</entry>
<entry/>
<entry><media id="eip-id1168469712989" alt="."><image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/CNX_BMath_Figure_09_01_027_img-02.png"/></media></entry>
</row>
<row>
<entry>Combine like terms.</entry>
